<chapter xml:id="ch_motion" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Motion</title>
<introduction>
    <p>Now that you have a foundation in vectors, you will begin looking at your first major physics topic: motion.</p>
				
	</introduction>
		
    <objectives>
      
      <introduction><p>After successful completion of this chapter, you will be able to:</p></introduction>
<ol>
<li><p>Analyze translational motion using a motion diagram.</p></li>
<li><p>Apply the particle model to analyze translational motion.</p></li>
<li><p>Define average velocity.</p></li>
<li><p>Define average acceleration.</p></li>
<li><p>Define instantaneous velocity.</p></li>
<li><p>Define instantaneous acceleration.</p></li>
<li><p>Analyze motion in a position versus time graph.</p></li>
<li><p>Draw a correlation between motion diagrams and position versus time graphs.</p></li>
<li><p>Draw a velocity versus time and acceleration versus time graph from a position versus time graph and vice versa.</p></li>
<li><p>Determine the sign of position, velocity and acceleration within a defined coordinate system.</p></li>
<li><p>Determine position, distance, velocity and speed from graphs of position and velocity versus time.</p></li>
<li><p>Make sense of a symbolic quantity using covariational reasoning.</p></li>
</ol>

</objectives>
	 
